org.fluidity.composition.spi

Interface ComponentFactory.Container

  • Enclosing interface:
    ComponentFactory

    public static interface ComponentFactory.Container
    A ComponentFactory.Resolver that can create local resolvers.

    Usage

    The ComponentFactory shows the basic pattern of using this interface.

    In case the component created by the factory is not a Fluid Tools component, a more elaborate pattern is required. In the below example, MyComponentImpl is not a Fluid Tools component while its dependency, LocalDependency, is: 

     @Component(api = MyComponent.class)
 final class MyComponentFactory implements ComponentFactory {

   public Instance resolve(final ComponentContext context, final Container dependencies) throws Exception {
     final ComponentFactory.Bindings locals = registry -> registry.bindComponent(LocalDependency.class);
     final Container container = dependencies.resolver(MyComponentImpl.class, locals));

     final Constructor<?> constructor = MyComponentImpl.class.getConstructor(…);
     final Dependency<?>[] arguments = container.resolve(null, constructor);

     return Instance.of(MyComponentImpl.class, registry -> {
       locals.bind(registry);
       registry.bindComponent(constructor.newInstance(container.instantiate(arguments)));
     });
   }
 }
 
     final class MyComponentImpl implements MyComponent {

   MyComponentImpl(final LocalDependency local, …) {
     …
   }

   …
 }
 
     @Component(automatic = false)
 final class LocalDependency {
   …
 }
    If LocalDependency were not a Fluid Tools component either, rather binding its class directly, its dependencies would have to be discovered using more specific methods of ComponentFactory.Container, similarly how MyComponentImpl was handled.

    • Method Detail

      • instance

        ComponentFactory.Instance instance(Class<?> type,
                                   ComponentFactory.Bindings bindings)
                            throws Exception
        Convenience method to resolve and instantiate a local component. Calling this method on a container instance is equivalent to the following sequence: 
           final Instance resolve(final ComponentContext context, Container dependencies) throws Exception {
     final Class type = …
     final ComponentFactory.Bindings locals = …

     dependencies.resolver(locals).discover(type);

     return Instance.of(type, locals);
   }
        Parameters:
        type - the component class to add to resolve and instantiate.
        bindings - the local bindings necessary to instantiate the component.
        Returns:
        an object that will bind the created components and its dependencies.
        Throws:
        Exception - whatever bindings throw.

      • instance

        ComponentFactory.Instance instance(Class<?> type)
        Convenience method to resolve and instantiate a local component. Calling this method on an instance, container is equivalent to the following sequence: 
           final Instance resolve(final ComponentContext context, Container dependencies) throws Exception {
     final Class type = …
     return dependencies.instance(type, registry -> registry.bindComponent(type));
   }
        Parameters:
        type - the component class to add to resolve and instantiate.
        Returns:
        an object that will bind the created components and its dependencies.

      • resolver

        ComponentFactory.Resolver resolver()
        Returns a resolver without any local dependencies bound. The returned container can be used to resolve dependencies of some component.
        Returns:
        a container to resolve dependencies.

      • resolver

        ComponentFactory.Resolver resolver(Class<?> type)
        Returns a resolver without bound type bound as local dependency, but with component context derived from the given type. The returned container can be used to resolve dependencies of the given type or some other component.
        Parameters:
        type - component class to derive context from; may be null.
        Returns:
        a container to resolve dependencies.

      • resolver

        ComponentFactory.Resolver resolver(ComponentFactory.Bindings bindings)

      • resolver

        ComponentFactory.Resolver resolver(Class<?> type,
                                   ComponentFactory.Bindings bindings)
                            throws Exception
        Returns a resolver with local dependencies bound by the given bindings and component context derived from the given type. The returned container can be used to resolve dependencies of the given type or some other component.
